question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: a.	Repeat the blood cultures x 2, administer broad spectrum IV antibiotic within 3 hours, and draw a lactate.

question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: b.	Draw a lactate only since the patient has had blood cultures within the last 6 hours and is already on antibiotics.

question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: c.	Notify the provider and expect orders for an IV broad spectrum antibiotic and a lactate to meet the remaining bundle requirement.

question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: d.	Notify the provider and expect orders for repeat blood cultures, IV broad spectrum antibiotic, and a lactate. And the nurse should wait to administer the antibiotic until the blood cultures are done.

question_text: Ms Cruise has been on vacation and missed her first day of Gleevec therapy. She asks you if she can take 2 the following day like she used to do with her birth control. What would you recommend?
answer_text: A. Yes, you can double your dose any time you miss a dose as long as you don't take more than 2 days together.

question_text: Ms Cruise has been on vacation and missed her first day of Gleevec therapy. She asks you if she can take 2 the following day like she used to do with her birth control. What would you recommend?
answer_text: B. No, you should never double the dose of your medication. Skip the missed dose if it's too close to your next dose or take the missed dose as soon as you remember if it's not too close to your next dose.

question_text: Ms Cruise has been on vacation and missed her first day of Gleevec therapy. She asks you if she can take 2 the following day like she used to do with her birth control. What would you recommend?
answer_text: C. Yes, you can take as many doses as needed to get back on schedule.

question_text: Ms Cruise has been on vacation and missed her first day of Gleevec therapy. She asks you if she can take 2 the following day like she used to do with her birth control. What would you recommend?
answer_text: D. No, don't double the dose. Skip a day as a wash out and start your therapy again from day 1.

Mr Brown tells you that the physician has changed his therapy and he no longer needs his Cabometyx. He tells you that he met another patient in his support group that is taking the same medication and wants to give him the remaining pills.

What do you recommend?

National Suicide Data

According to the CDC, one person dies by suicide every 15 minutes, over 40,000 suicides are completed per year as compared to 18,000 homicides, the highest risk group are individuals ages 18 -25 and 45 percent of people who died by suicide saw their primary care provider within a month of their death.

Which of the following are FALSE concerning Tracheostomy patients during transports?
answer_text: A.	Respiratory Therapist must accompany the patient during the entire transport (must stay with patient).

question_text: Which of the following are FALSE concerning Tracheostomy patients during transports?
answer_text: B.	A bag valve mask, obturator or spare tracheostomy must also accompany the patient during transport in the event the airway is displaced.

question_text: Which of the following are FALSE concerning Tracheostomy patients during transports?
answer_text: C.	If a patient is having an MRI or CT performed, the Respiratory Therapist must stay in the MRI or CT room and be able to access the patient in the event of an emergency at all times.

question_text: Which of the following are FALSE concerning Tracheostomy patients during transports?
answer_text: D.	Respiratory Therapist must accompany the patient during transport, and may leave patient (if stable) in area where procedure is to be performed

question_text: Patient has a history of COPD is admitted with Pneumonia. Home meds on MED REC form completed by the nurse include ProAir 2puffs PRN, 0.5mg Pulmicort and 15mcg Brovana BID, 0.5mg Albuterol Q4, and Advair 250/50. What changes would you recommend to the physician?
answer_text: A.	None. These are home meds and we don't recommend changing home meds.

question_text: Patient has a history of COPD is admitted with Pneumonia. Home meds on MED REC form completed by the nurse include ProAir 2puffs PRN, 0.5mg Pulmicort and 15mcg Brovana BID, 0.5mg Albuterol Q4, and Advair 250/50. What changes would you recommend to the physician?
answer_text: B.	Keep meds as listed but add 0.5mg Atrovent Q4 and Spiriva 1 puff daily

question_text: Patient has a history of COPD is admitted with Pneumonia. Home meds on MED REC form completed by the nurse include ProAir 2puffs PRN, 0.5mg Pulmicort and 15mcg Brovana BID, 0.5mg Albuterol Q4, and Advair 250/50. What changes would you recommend to the physician?
answer_text: C.	Change Albuterol to Xopenex per interchange policy & add Spiriva 1 puff daily

question_text: Patient has a history of COPD is admitted with Pneumonia. Home meds on MED REC form completed by the nurse include ProAir 2puffs PRN, 0.5mg Pulmicort and 15mcg Brovana BID, 0.5mg Albuterol Q4, and Advair 250/50. What changes would you recommend to the physician?
answer_text: D.	Recommend discontinuing one of the duplications of inhaled corticosteroid and long-acting beta agonist medications, consider adding 0.5mg Atrovent Q4.

question_text: A patient admitted with pneumonia has Incentive Spirometry ordered Q2w/a. Predicted Goal is 2750 but patient is only achieving 1300ml at start of therapy.  What is the percentage the patient is achieving and what changes would you make per protocol?
answer_text: A.	75%: Change SMI to PRN for nursing to follow, notify RN & Document in EMR

question_text: A patient admitted with pneumonia has Incentive Spirometry ordered Q2w/a. Predicted Goal is 2750 but patient is only achieving 1300ml at start of therapy.  What is the percentage the patient is achieving and what changes would you make per protocol?
answer_text: B.	50% - 75%: Continue SMI for now, start IPPB in 3 days; Document in EMR

question_text: A patient admitted with pneumonia has Incentive Spirometry ordered Q2w/a. Predicted Goal is 2750 but patient is only achieving 1300ml at start of therapy.  What is the percentage the patient is achieving and what changes would you make per protocol?
answer_text: C.	50%-75%: Start IBBP therapy and discontinue SMI; Document in EMR

question_text: A patient admitted with pneumonia has Incentive Spirometry ordered Q2w/a. Predicted Goal is 2750 but patient is only achieving 1300ml at start of therapy.  What is the percentage the patient is achieving and what changes would you make per protocol?
answer_text: D.	<50%: Start IBBP and continue use of SMI BID or after each IPPB treatment to measure volume improvement until patient can achieve goal >50% for 2 consecutive visits;  Document both in EMR

question_text: A patient admitted with pneumonia has Incentive Spirometry ordered Q2w/a. Predicted Goal is 2750 but patient is only achieving 1300ml at start of therapy.  What is the percentage the patient is achieving and what changes would you make per protocol?
answer_text: E.	<50%: continue SMI, reassess in 72 hours for need for IPPB; Document in EMR
